                            jump to other results
                        </a></div></div><ol class="sense_single" htag="ol"><li class="sense" hclass="sense" id="addison_sng_1" htag="li"><span class="sensetop" hclass="sensetop" htag="span"><span class="def" htag="span" hclass="def">(1672-1719) an English writer and poet who was also active in politics. With his friend <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/richard-steele" title="Richard Steele definition"><span class="ndv">Richard Steele</span></a> he started the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/the-spectator#the_spectator_topg_1" title="Spectator definition"><span class="ndv">Spectator</span></a>. He wrote many poems and a <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/tragic" title="tragic definition"><span class="ndv">tragic</span></a> play, <span class="ebi">Cato</span> (1713), but he is remembered mainly for his essays in the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/the-spectator#the_spectator_topg_1" title="Spectator definition"><span class="ndv">Spectator</span></a> and the <a class="Ref" href="https://www.oxfordlearnersdictionaries.com/definition/english/tatler#the_tatler_topg_1" title="Tatler definition"><span class="ndv">Tatler</span></a>, written in a simple, direct style.</span></span>    <div id="ring-links-box">
